verbose_text: The central phosphorus atom of the triphosphane part of the P 2 (SiH)-P 3 backbone appears in the room temperature spectrum as a triplet of triplets at -106.6 ppm with splittings of 163 Hz and 16 Hz due to coupling with the adjacent and remote ferrocene bonded phosphorus atoms, which themselves give rise to broad resonances between -59 to -34 ppm (nu 1/2 = ~ 1300 Hz, Si bound P-atoms3b) and 2 to 20 ppm (nu 1/2 = ~ 1600 Hz, P bound terminal phosphorus atoms).
